Docker for Continuous Testing 芒聙聰 Selenium Tests in Containerized Environments
Objectives
Design and deploy a containerized Selenium Grid (a distributed browser automation infrastructure) using Docker and Docker Compose from scratch
Implement a Python pytest test suite that executes against the containerized grid and produces structured HTML and JUnit XML reports
Integrate the containerized test pipeline into a Jenkins CI server so that every code push triggers a full Selenium test run automatically
Prerequisites
Comfort navigating and editing files on a Linux/Ubuntu command line
Basic Python programming knowledge, including writing functions and using third-party libraries
Familiarity with the concept of automated software testing and what a browser automation tool does
Lab Environment
You will work on a dedicated AWS EC2 Ubuntu instance provided by Al Nafi. The instance has a base Ubuntu installation; you will install all required tools in Task 1.

Task 1: Install and Verify the Complete Toolchain
Step 1.1 芒聙聰 Install Docker Engine, Docker Compose, Python 3, pip, and Git
Install Docker Engine using the official apt repository, then install the remaining tools from Ubuntu's package index.

# Remove any conflicting legacy Docker packages
sudo apt-get remove -y docker docker-engine docker.io containerd runc 2>/dev/null || true

# Add Docker's official GPG key and repository
sudo apt-get update -y
sudo apt-get install -y ca-certificates curl gnupg lsb-release

sudo install -m 0755 -d /etc/apt/keyrings
curl -fsSL https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu/gpg \
  | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg
sudo chmod a+r /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg

# Official current guide if this URL changes: https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/ubuntu/
sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list <<'EOF'
deb [arch=amd64 signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg] https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu jammy stable
EOF

sudo apt-get update -y
sudo apt-get install -y docker-ce docker-ce-cli containerd.io docker-buildx-plugin docker-compose-plugin

# Allow the current user to run Docker without sudo
sudo usermod -aG docker "$USER"
newgrp docker <<'GROUPEOF'
echo "Docker group active"
GROUPEOF
Troubleshoot this step:

Error seen: E: Malformed entry 1 in list file /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list 芒聙聰 the file contains a literal backslash or is split across lines.
Recovery: cat /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list 芒聙聰 the file must be a single unbroken line; delete it with sudo rm /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list and re-run the tee heredoc block above.
Official docs: https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/ubuntu/
# Install Python 3, pip, and Git
sudo apt-get install -y python3 python3-pip python3-venv git

# Verify every tool is present
docker --version
docker compose version
python3 --version
pip3 --version
git --version
Confirmation: All five version strings print without error. If docker --version returns "permission denied", log out and back in so the group membership takes effect, then re-run.

Step 1.2 芒聙聰 Pull the Selenium Standalone Chrome image and confirm it runs
Pull the official Selenium image and start a temporary container to confirm the WebDriver endpoint responds.

# Pull the image 芒聙聰 this may take 2-3 minutes on first run
docker pull selenium/standalone-chrome:4.18.1

# Start a short-lived container to verify the endpoint
docker run -d \
  --name sel-verify \
  -p 4444:4444 \
  --shm-size=2g \
  selenium/standalone-chrome:4.18.1

# Wait for the node to register (the grid needs ~10 seconds to initialise)
sleep 15

# Query the grid status endpoint
curl -fsSL http://localhost:4444/status

# Remove the verification container
docker stop sel-verify && docker rm sel-verify
Troubleshoot this step:

Error seen: curl: (7) Failed to connect to localhost port 4444: Connection refused 芒聙聰 the container has not finished starting.
Recovery: Run docker logs sel-verify to check startup progress; if the log shows Started Selenium Standalone, wait another 10 seconds and retry the curl command.
Official docs: https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/docker-selenium
Confirmation: The curl command returns a JSON object containing "ready": true and a "nodes" array with at least one entry listing "browserName": "chrome".

Task 2: Design and Deploy a Containerised Selenium Test Suite
Problem Statement
Design and implement a self-contained testing system that satisfies all of the following constraints:

A docker-compose.yml file defines three services: a Selenium Hub, a Chrome browser node, and a Python test-runner container built from a Dockerfile you write.
The test-runner image installs all Python dependencies from a requirements.txt at build time and contains no pre-written test logic 芒聙聰 you write all test code from scratch.
The pytest suite must contain at least four test functions spread across at least two test classes; each test must navigate to a real public URL, interact with at least one page element, and make at least one assertion about the page state.
All tests execute against the Selenium Hub over the Docker Compose internal network (not localhost); the Hub URL must be read from an environment variable so it can be overridden without rebuilding the image.
Running docker compose up --build --abort-on-container-exit must start the grid, execute all tests, and exit cleanly.
Acceptance Criteria

docker compose up --build --abort-on-container-exit completes with exit code 0, all four test functions are reported as PASSED in the terminal output, and an HTML report file is written to a host-mounted reports/ directory.
Running docker compose up --build --abort-on-container-exit a second time without any code changes produces identical pass/fail results, confirming the environment is fully reproducible and stateless between runs.
Task 3: Integrate the Test Pipeline into Jenkins CI
Problem Statement
Design and implement a Jenkins CI pipeline that satisfies all of the following constraints:

Jenkins runs as a Docker container on the same EC2 instance; its container must have access to the host Docker socket so it can start and stop the Selenium Compose stack as part of the pipeline.
A Jenkinsfile in the project root defines a declarative pipeline with at minimum four named stages: Checkout, Start Grid, Run Tests, and Teardown.
The Run Tests stage must invoke the Compose stack, wait for the Selenium Hub to report "ready": true before launching tests (do not use a fixed sleep), and capture the pytest exit code to mark the build as FAILED if any test fails.
The pipeline must archive the HTML report and the JUnit XML results file as build artifacts so they are accessible from the Jenkins build page.
A SCM poll trigger must be configured so Jenkins checks for changes every five minutes; you must demonstrate this by pushing a deliberate test failure, observing the build turn red, fixing it, and observing the build turn green 芒聙聰 all without manually clicking "Build Now".
Acceptance Criteria

The Jenkins build page for a passing run shows all four stages green, lists the HTML report as a downloadable artifact, and the JUnit trend graph shows at least two consecutive passing builds.
Introducing a failing assertion into one test function, committing, and waiting no more than ten minutes causes Jenkins to automatically trigger a new build that reports the correct number of failures in the JUnit results, then a subsequent fix commit causes the build to return to green automatically.
Expected Outcomes
A fully containerised Selenium Grid and Python test suite that any team member can reproduce by running a single docker compose command on a clean Ubuntu machine.
A Jenkins pipeline that provides continuous, automatic feedback on test health after every code change without any manual intervention.
Conclusion
This lab demonstrates that containerised browser testing eliminates "works on my machine" failures by making the browser, the WebDriver server, and the test runner all version-pinned and reproducible. Integrating that container stack into Jenkins closes the feedback loop so regressions are caught within minutes of a commit rather than at release time. The patterns you have built here 芒聙聰 a Compose-defined grid, a parameterised Hub URL, and a pipeline that waits for readiness rather than sleeping 芒聙聰 are directly transferable to production CI environments at any scale.
